<div class="post-date">Sep 21</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/972.html" title="Just under flood stage"> Just under flood stage</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>I really need to get down to see the river. I think I&#8217;ll get up early to do so tomorrow. The Ohio takes on a very different look when it is high. If it wasn&#8217;t for the rushing water, it would seem more like a lake.</p>

	<p>It&#8217;s around the 444 foot level with flood stage at 451. It&#8217;s peaking now and is supposed to be down to 440 by Friday, still a bank full, but definitely no flooding.</p>

	<p>Darlene said it&#8217;s a mess down there. Tons of debris floating down river. She said she thought she saw a &#8216;fridge float down. Our daily newspaper&#8217;s photographer told her he thought he saw an outhouse. Lots of barrels and trees.</p>

	<p>Lots of people have been down by the river watching it go by. Guys sitting at the side of the street fishing&#8212;normally you&#8217;d have to walk <strong>down</strong> a good 20 feet to get to the river. Nearby, E.G. (the Egyptian goose on the riverfront, not me) was huddling with his new found cohort Aneg (ANother Egyptian Goose). All the geese were displaced to parkland across the street.</p>

	<p>It seems sad that we&#8217;re watching the river flow by with an odd fascination as towns in Pennsylvania, W.Virginia and North Carolina are getting swept away by the remnents of Ivan. We didn&#8217;t get the rain so there is a disconnect when we watch the swollen river.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
