<div class="post-date">Mar  8</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/892.html" title="Egyptian goose followup"> Egyptian goose followup</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>When we saw an Egyptian goose  on our riverfront (photo at left) we were curious how a native African bird could end up on the Ohio River. <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/archives/000274.html">(read earlier post)</a></p>

	<p>Thus I sent an email to the Louisville Zoo asking if they had an idea how he could have gotten here.</p>

	<p>Here is the response:</p>

	<p><blockquote>Mr. Yarnetsky, I have just received an answer from our lead Bird-keeper, Mr. Johnson.</p>

	<p>Yes, the photo is indeed an Egyptian goose. Mr. Johnson does not think that it is from the Zoo.  Egyptian Geese are pretty common in Kentucky through mail order companies.  They are usually also found for sale at the Kentucky State Fair each week.</p>

	<p>Good eye in spotting the bird!<br />
Gary Michael</blockquote></p>

	<p>An unusual find, but apparently not THAT unusual. We&#8217;ll take a sacred Egyptian bird on our riverfront nonetheless.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
