<div class="post-date">Feb  6</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/872.html" title="I&#8217;m a published restaurant critic"> I&#8217;m a published restaurant critic</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>When Darlene&#8217;s sister&#8217;s family came to visit, we all descended on <a title="Mundt's Candies" href="http://www.mundtscandies.com">Mundt&#8217;s Candies</a> here in downtown Madison. I know the owner, Maryanne Imes, but the gang had such a good time that I wrote up a review so others could enjoy this awesome place.</p>

	<p>Read my first <a title="Roadfood.com" href="http://www.roadfood.com/Reviews/Writeup.aspx?ReviewID=2026&#38;RefID=1962">Roadfood.com review</a>. I had a lot of fun writing it. I may do some exploring for an excuse to write another.</p>

	<p>For those not familiar with the book &#8220;Road Food&#8221; or it&#8217;s companion website, here&#8217;s some background.</p>

	<p>Jane and Michael Stern have traveled the country ump-teen times over the past couple of decades sampling the best food from backroad and Main Street restaurants. The result was &#8220;Roadfood&#8221; a pretty cool compendium of good eats.</p>

	<p>When this guy says a hamburger or tenderloin is good, trust him. He knows his stuff. He also appears weekly on the public radio show <a href="http://www.splendidtable.org">The Splendid Table</a> and is a columnist for Epicurious and Gourmet.</p>



 
<div class="line"></div>

<div class="smallcat">Posted in <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?c=Madison">Madison</a></div>
<div class="smalluser"> by <a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?author=E.G.+Yarnetsky">E.G. Yarnetsky</a></div>
